In truth, if you really care about it, you can take a policy based design approach to this and have explicit rules for when you may or may not do type erasure. It&#x27;s definitely a bit of work, but you can actually get full compile_time type safety and yet avoid having duplicative code with various tricks like (this skips over a lot of the pain and isn&#x27;t really how you&#x27;d do it... just illustrative):<p><pre><code>    template <std::size_t N>
    struct raw {
        template <typename U>
        constexpr raw(U x, std::enable_if<.....>);

        template <typename U>
        constexpr operator U();
    };

    template <template ContainerType, typename T, std::enable_if<std::is_trivially_convertible<T, ....> > >
    struct somewhat_erased_container :  private ContainerType<raw<sizeof(T)>> {
    };
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s particularly easy to do with containers of pointers (of course).
